The Two Different Things

Ingress Resource              Ingress Controller
------------------------------------------------------------
What it is
Just a YAML config/rules      Actual running Pod

Runs as Pod?
❌ No                          ✅ Yes

Does work?
❌ No                          ✅ Yes

Who creates it?
You (developer)               Installed separately (e.g. nginx)

Example
Your ingress.yaml above       nginx-ingress-controller pod
-------------------------------------------------------------------

HTTP Ingress
# ingress.yaml
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: my-app
  annotations:
    kubernetes.io/ingress.class: nginx   # ← tells which controller to use
spec:
  rules:
  - host: myapp.example.com
    http:
      paths:
      - path: /api
        pathType: Prefix
        backend:
          service:
            name: api-service            # ← matches Service name below
            port:
              number: 80
      - path: /
        pathType: Prefix
        backend:
          service:
            name: web-service            # ← matches Service name below
            port:
              number: 80

Ingress (defines routing rules):
. Ingress Resource — routing rules (you write this)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
HTTPS Ingress
-------------
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: myapp-ingress
  namespace: myapp
  annotations:
    nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/ssl-redirect: "true"   # Force HTTP → HTTPS
spec:
  tls:
    - hosts:
        - myapp.example.com          # Your domain
      secretName: myapp-tls-secret   # TLS(SSL) certificate secret
  rules:
    - host: myapp.example.com
      http:
        paths:
          - path: /
            pathType: Prefix
            backend:
              service:
                name: myapp-service
                port:
                  number: 80
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
we need to expose ingress right?

Yes! The Ingress Controller itself needs to be exposed externely
The Ingress Controller is just a Pod running inside the cluster — it needs a way to receive external traffic. This is where one LoadBalancer type Service is used.

Service (type: LoadBalancer)   
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# This is created automatically by Helm — shown here for understanding only
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: ingress-nginx-controller
  namespace: ingress-nginx
spec:
  type: LoadBalancer        # ← Triggers AWS to provision an ALB
  selector:
    app.kubernetes.io/name: ingress-nginx   # ← Points to NGINX controller pod
  ports:
  - name: http
    port: 80
    targetPort: 80
  - name: https
    port: 443
    targetPort: 443

